        {
            "id": "cf7236c27ea14630adfb8",
            "questionText": "A scientist is studying the Earth's energy balance. Assuming Earth radiates as a blackbody with an emissivity '$!$\\epsilon$!$' of 0.6 and an albedo '$!$\\alpha$!$' of 0.3, the solar constant '$!$S$!$' is 1400 '$!$\\frac{W}{m^2}$!$', and the average surface temperature of the Earth is '$!$T$!$' = 288 K. If the temperature of space '$!$T_s$!$' is 0 K, what is the net power radiated '$!$P_{net}$!$' per unit area in '$!$\\frac{W}{m^2}$!$'?",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "37ca775e2b67479693a7e",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the correct formula that expresses the net power radiated by a body using the Stefan\u2013Boltzmann law. Please select the correct formula from the following options.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "e3a5ec68-44b5-4731-ba26-1e6d6d1e4970"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$P_{net} = \\epsilon \\sigma (T^4 - T_s^4) $!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$P_{net} = \\alpha \\sigma T^4 $!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$P_{net} = \\epsilon S (T - T_s) $!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "02f1f66aa92b45a797887",
